The erroneous code fails because the variable named variable lacks an initial value before the print statement executes. This causes a compilation error since Java requires local variables to be initialized before use. The fix involves assigning a value to variable prior to printing it.

Below are the corrected and additional classes that manage the same variable concept while performing different operations.

Class One fixes the original error by initializing the string value.
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

Class Two assigns a completely new value to the variable and displays it.
```java
public class ValueAssigner {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "New Assignment";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

Class Three concatenates the original variable with another string and prints the result.
```java
public class StringConcatenator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        String extra = " and Java";
        variable = variable + extra;
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

Class Four compares the variable to another string and returns a boolean result.
```java
public class StringComparer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        String target = "Hello world";
        boolean result = variable.equals(target);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```
